An important reason for using neural networks is to substitute the
&#39;black box&#39; of a network for the many (perhapse thousands) of lines of
code to create the behaviour &#39;by hand.&#39;
The XOR problem is an interesting proof of concept, but it is not
usefull as a product. A control system that can navigate a car over a
bridge, around a corner, and through a field of boulders could be worth
two million dollars (the next DARPA grand challenge award pot). In
comparsion to the handwritten code, several hundered nodes processed in
for() loop are much much faster than the math that goes into handwritten
code.
Like ken said, evaluating the behaviour of XOR is very simple, but
evaluating the behaviour of a single network to do many complex
behaviours takes a very long time.
Tylers Evolveing Humans presents a very easy use interface with a visual
of the evaluation process. If you want to see a network evolve over
time, that is the best software package I&#39;ve seen. Over a thousand
generations, with a population of 128, I was able to observe a human
shaped charachter learn how to walk in a matter of two days on a 1.1 GHz
AMD. Coding the human to walk even the step and a half it made at that
point would have taken far longer, and taken much more space.

chad

